Hello,

In my experience, the difference between the ways the two
systems handle version identification keywords is enough to
make RCS much more attractive than SCCS.

This is probably due to the fact that developers at our company
(Evolving Systems, Inc. (ESI)) rely heavily on a "reference
area", which is a directory tree that contains all the latest
checked-in versions of a set of files.

They go into the reference area and start looking around, and before
they know it they're editing a file.  They try to save it and get
a "permission denied" error, whereupon they realize they
haven't checked the file out.  So they run a script to lock the
file, so that they don't have to edit it all over again.

When this is done using SCCS, the keywords remain expanded.  That
is, the values are now constants rather than keywords.  After one
checkin these values are wrong.  (One really frustrating aspect of
this difference is that very few people seem to understand this
problem.)

Of course this problem, like many others, can be solved by creating
a shell interface script that searches for a given pattern in every
file (the pattern must be different for different types of files)
and replaces part of this pattern with fresh keywords every time a
file is checked in.  (Note that just because something's possible
does not mean it's easy.)

That's the view from where I sit.

Following is a FAQ that I got from someone, I can't remember whom.
I'm surprised no one has posted this yet.  Perhaps the Free Software
Foundation is considered a manufacturer, and my posting this is a
major faux pas?  Please note that I do not work for them, but rather
work for about 300 developers, most of whom do not care about keywords,
rather, they just want to check their file in.

