In article 61u@spot.twinsun.com, eggert@twinsun.com (Paul Eggert) writes:
>treacy@slipknot.Eng.Sun.COM (John Treacy) writes:

>> The SCCS implementation is better suited (performance wise) for many of the
>> tasks that SW/TW has to do.
>
>I'm skeptical.  Do you have performance measurements, or are you just guessing?
>If SCCS must always read the entire history file, whereas RCS only
>needs to read an initial prefix, I don't see why SCCS is ``better
>suited (performance wise)''.

There are some tasks that have more in common with prt and rlog than get/co.
For instance, SW/TW has a graphical frontend to SCCS, VersionTool, which
allows you to do sccs operations by point and click. Getting the delta
history and presenting it requires us to read just the top of the SCCS
file. RCS on the other hand keeps delta comments with the deltas, requiring
a read of the entire file to display the delta history. There are other
parts of the product (SW/TW) which also benefit from having the entire delta 
table at the head of the file.

John




